INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (91,41,'Twenty Minutes of Guitar, No Pressure (XSL001)','I started keeping a tiny guitar log because I kept “practicing” in my head and never actually playing. Tonight was just quiet rhythm work: slow strums, clean chord changes, and keeping time without rushing. No fancy licks, no chasing speed. I set a timer for 20 minutes and stopped when it rang, even though I wanted to keep going. It’s weirdly comforting to end on purpose. Tomorrow I’ll repeat the same set and see if it feels easier.',5,1,0,0,1,1,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(92,62,'Three Bugs I Dodged on My Class Project (XSL002)','I’m finishing a programming project in the lab and I finally learned (again) that most of my “mystery issues” are self-inflicted. Today’s wins: I set up a clean folder structure before writing anything, tested one function at a time, and stopped hard-coding paths like a clown. Also: saving sample inputs in a separate file made debugging so much faster. The setup isn’t fancy, but it’s stable and predictable, which is all I want during a deadline week.',6,1,0,5,1,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(93,44,'Golden Hour Between the Track and the Library (XSL003)','I walked past the track bleachers and the light near the library was doing that soft, quiet thing where everything looks slower than it is. I took a few shots from standing height and they felt flat, so I crouched lower and let the railings and steps layer the frame. Minimal edits after—just a small exposure tweak—because the colors were already close to perfect. I’m trying to train myself to notice light first, then composition, instead of the other way around.',4,1,0,6,2,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(94,62,'My Low-Effort Source Organizer Actually Stuck (XSL004)','I’ve tried fancy citation apps and then immediately abandoned them, so I went back to something embarrassingly simple: one paper notebook + a single page per class for sources. Each entry is just: where I found it, why I saved it, and one sentence I can quote later. The best part is the “done” page at the back—when I finish reading something, I move it there so tomorrow’s list doesn’t feel endless. It’s not perfect, but it’s sustainable.',2,1,0,1,1,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(95,68,'The White Shirt Outfit That Doesn’t Feel Stiff (XSL005)','I used to avoid white shirts because they always looked too “formal” on me, but I found a way to make it feel like normal campus clothes. I wore it slightly oversized with relaxed pants and my most beat-up sneakers, and suddenly it looked intentional instead of try-hard. The real trick is choosing pieces that can rotate with everything else in my closet, because I’m not buying a new outfit for every week. Comfort first, repeatability second, everything else last.',7,1,0,6,0,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(96,55,'A Finals Plan That Doesn’t Make Me Panic (XSL006)','I rewrote my finals plan today because the old version was basically a doom scroll in checklist form. Instead of one giant list, I split everything into 25–30 minute blocks and assigned them to specific days. The biggest change: I end each session by writing the next tiny step on the last page, so tomorrow I can start without negotiating with myself. I’m also leaving “buffer blocks” for the stuff that always takes longer than I think. It feels calmer already.',2,1,0,6,4,2,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(97,63,'Monday Outfit: Comfy Enough for a Long Lecture (XSL007)','Mondays are not the day I’m experimenting, so I went with my safest formula: one clean base layer, one warmer outer layer, and shoes I can walk across campus in without thinking. I’m trying to build a closet where everything repeats well, because laundry timing is chaotic and my budget is not infinite. The outfit looked better than expected in the dorm mirror, mostly because the colors were simple and the fit wasn’t too tight anywhere. Practical wins count too.',7,1,0,5,3,3,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(98,55,'Rehearsal Notes From a Small Practice Room (XSL008)','Our club rehearsal was short but productive, and I’m trying to write down what actually helped instead of just saying “it was fine.” We spent most of the time tightening transitions and picking a tempo that feels steady, not rushed. I also realized I practice better when I separate “work mode” songs from “comfort songs,” so I don’t drift into playing the same easy chorus for an hour. Even 20 focused minutes beats two hours of wandering around.',5,1,0,3,2,1,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(99,60,'Second-Floor Cafeteria Noodles: Fast, Filling, Cheap (XSL009)','Tried the noodle counter on the second floor after class because the line looked shorter than usual. I wrote down the basics like a nerd: wait time, price, and whether it actually keeps me full through evening study. The broth was simple but comforting, and the portion was bigger than I expected for the cost. The best part was how fast it moved—no awkward standing around with a tray for ten minutes. If you hate crowds, go a little before the rush and you’ll be fine.',1,1,0,6,2,2,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:31',0),(100,52,'Freshman Packing List That Saved Me Three Trips (XSL010)','I wish someone had told me that moving in is mostly about avoiding repeat trips. This week I updated my freshman packing list based on what I actually used: a small toolkit for loose screws, a power strip with enough outlets, a laundry bag that stands up, and one storage bin that fits under the bed. I also noted the timing—elevators get chaotic right after lunch. The list looks boring, but it genuinely makes dorm life smoother. I’ll update it again after midterms.',10,1,0,0,4,2,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(101,52,'My quiet late-night playlist for the study room corner (XSL011)','I’ve been camping in the study room corner lately, and I finally made a late-night listening list that matches the vibe instead of distracting me. I split it into three mini blocks: “warm-up” (lo-fi + soft indie), “deep focus” (instrumental, steady tempo), and “cool down” (slow acoustic). It sounds picky, but it actually helps me stop doom-scrolling between chapters. Also: 20 minutes of focused listening + work beats two hours of half-trying. I’ll tweak it after finals week.',5,1,0,3,3,1,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(102,51,'Second-floor cafeteria late-night snack run: actually solid (XSL012)','After an evening class, my friend dragged me to the late-night window near the second-floor cafeteria and I’m glad I didn’t just go back to the dorm hungry. The line looked scary, but it moved faster than I expected (about 8–10 minutes). I grabbed something warm and salty plus a drink, and the portion felt very “student budget friendly.” The best part is it doesn’t taste like a compromise meal. If you go, avoid the exact end-of-class rush by 15 minutes and you’ll be fine.',1,1,0,8,4,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(103,44,'A low-effort weekly workout plan that I’m still doing (XSL013)','I’ve tried “new me” workout plans before and they always die after three days, so I went embarrassingly simple this week. Two short runs, one bodyweight day, and one long stretch session. No fancy gear, no gym intimidation, just stuff I can do even when assignments pile up. The biggest change wasn’t my stamina—it was my mood. I stop feeling like I’m trapped in my chair all day. If you’re starting, set the bar low enough that you can’t talk yourself out of it.',8,1,0,7,4,2,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(104,51,'Dorm desk refresh that made studying less annoying (XSL014)','My desk was turning into a pile of cables, snack wrappers, and “important papers” that were not important at all. I did a quick reset today: cleared everything, wiped the surface, then only put back what I use daily (lamp, notebook, pen cup, charger). The rule I’m trying is: if it doesn’t help me study or sleep, it goes in a drawer. It took under 30 minutes but my brain feels way quieter. If you’re overwhelmed, start with trash first—instant progress.',10,1,0,3,4,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(105,59,'The weekly running plan that finally feels sustainable (XSL015)','I’m trying a “doable” running plan instead of the dramatic ones that wreck me. Three runs a week: one easy, one slightly faster, one just for time (no pace pressure). The trick is prepping like it’s a class: bottle filled, towel ready, and I leave 10 minutes at the end to cool down so I don’t feel destroyed walking back. It’s not intense, but it’s consistent—and that’s the point. If you’re busy, schedule the run like a meeting with yourself.',8,1,0,7,4,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(106,68,'East gate alley noodle counter: quick, warm, and cheap (XSL016)','Found a noodle counter near the east gate alley that’s perfect for those “I can’t cook and it’s too late” nights. It’s best with two or three friends so you can try different add-ons without spending much. I went right after class and the wait was okay, but I can tell the real chaos is the peak break time. The flavor is simple but comforting, and the portion is surprisingly filling for the price. I wrote down my order so I don’t forget next time.',1,1,0,6,2,5,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(107,51,'A vocabulary routine I can do even on chaotic days (XSL017)','I finally stopped pretending I’ll study vocabulary for an hour straight. My new routine is tiny blocks: 10 minutes review, 10 minutes new words, 5 minutes quick test. The best hack is keeping a “done list” on the last page—so when I sit down the next day, I don’t waste energy deciding where to start. I also only keep one deck active at a time, otherwise I spiral into “organizing” instead of learning. It’s boring, but boring is consistent.',2,1,0,0,4,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(108,46,'Rooftop rain reflections that made campus feel silent (XSL018)','I went up to the teaching building rooftop right after the rain and it felt like the whole campus got turned down to “quiet mode.” The puddles were basically mirrors, and the soft light made everything look smoother than usual. I kept edits super light because the real scene already had that calm gray-blue tone. If you want reflections, timing matters more than gear—go right after the rain stops, before people start walking through and breaking the surface. I’m going back next drizzle.',4,1,0,4,0,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(109,54,'Ginkgo walkway phone shots: low angle makes it look cinematic (XSL019)','I did a quick phone photo set on the ginkgo walkway and learned (again) that the angle matters more than filters. When I shot from eye level, it looked like a normal walk to class. When I crouched lower and let the trees frame the path, suddenly it had layers and depth. I also waited until the light softened so the leaves didn’t turn neon. If you’re trying campus photography, pick one small “rule” for the day—like only shooting low angle—and you’ll improve faster.',4,1,0,6,2,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(110,55,'This week’s guitar practice: fewer tricks, better timing (XSL020)','I kept a tiny guitar practice log this week and it helped more than I expected. Instead of chasing flashy technique, I focused on rhythm and clean transitions—basically the unglamorous stuff that makes everything sound better. I also paired practice with a short study playlist so I don’t drift into random riffs for an hour. The goal was consistency: 20–30 minutes, no excuses, stop before my hands get sloppy. It’s not a huge leap, but it finally feels like progress I can repeat.',5,1,0,5,2,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(111,52,'My dorm smart plug setup that actually behaves (XSL021)','I’ve been testing a tiny “smart” setup in our dorm corner near the computer lab and, surprisingly, it’s been stable. I started with the boring basics: one smart plug for the desk lamp and a timer routine for my fan so I’m not wasting power when I crash after late labs. The biggest win is reducing little decisions at night. If you’re on a student budget, skip the fancy extras first and just make one or two habits easier.',6,1,0,5,1,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(112,39,'A fall outfit formula that survives long campus days (XSL022)','I tried building a cheap fall outfit around one rule: I should be able to walk to class, sit in the library, and grab dinner without wanting to change. Neutral layers ended up being way more re-wearable than I expected. A slightly oversized knit + straight pants + comfy sneakers is boring in the best way. Everything mixes with older pieces, so I’m not buying “a whole new look.” Also: pockets matter more than trends when you’re carrying keys and a student ID.',7,1,0,2,0,5,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(113,50,'One-day city walk: lakeside start, zero stress (XSL023)','Did a one-day city walk starting at the lakeside path and it was the perfect reset after midterms. Booking transit early saved me more money than I thought, and I kept food simple with small local spots instead of chasing “must-try” lists. The best part was leaving gaps in the plan—wandering into side streets and parks made it feel like a real break, not another schedule. Next time I’m bringing a lighter bag and a portable charger from the start.',9,1,0,2,1,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(114,41,'My no-friction productivity setup for library days (XSL024)','I tweaked my productivity setup while camped at a library seat and it’s finally “boring” enough to stick. I keep one task list, one calendar, and one focus timer—nothing fancy, just reliable. The trick is setting defaults: same folder structure for every class, and a clean desktop so I don’t waste five minutes hunting files. I’m trying to optimize for real daily use, not the coolest features. It’s been surprisingly calming during busy weeks.',2,1,0,0,2,3,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:32',0),(115,45,'The only study room schedule I’ve kept for two weeks straight (XSL025)','I finally made a study room schedule that doesn’t collapse after three days. It’s basically: same time, same room, and fewer choices before I start. I pick one “anchor” block (mine is late afternoon), and I only plan the first 20 minutes so it’s easy to begin. I also write what I finished on the last page of my notebook, so tomorrow starts with momentum instead of guilt. It’s not magical, but it’s consistent—and that’s new for me.',2,1,0,7,1,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(116,52,'My 20-minute guitar log that keeps me honest (XSL026)','I started a guitar practice log and did the first entry sitting by the track bleachers, mostly because the air felt less stale than my room. I’m focusing on consistency over perfection: 20 minutes a day, even if it’s just chord changes and a slow strum pattern. I also grouped songs by mood so I can switch between “study break” and “wind down” without scrolling forever. Writing it down makes progress feel real, even on messy weeks.',5,1,0,1,1,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(117,46,'A productivity setup for dorm life (not influencer life) (XSL027)','I rebuilt my productivity setup at my dorm desk with the goal of “less maintenance.” I’m using a simple system: one place for tasks, one place for files, and one weekly review so I don’t wake up panicked on Monday. I used to chase new apps, but stability matters more when Wi‑Fi is weird and deadlines are real. The best change was making everything work offline first, then syncing when it can. It feels practical, not performative.',6,1,0,3,1,0,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(118,65,'The campus sunset shot I kept missing—until today (XSL028)','I finally got the campus sunset look I’ve been chasing from the teaching building rooftop. The biggest difference was timing: I showed up earlier and waited for the softer light instead of sprinting up at the last minute. I also shot from a lower angle so the railings and buildings layered nicely instead of feeling flat. It’s funny how small adjustments make photos feel intentional. Next time I want to try the same spot after rain for reflections.',4,1,0,8,3,2,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(119,65,'A simple morning run log that changed my mood (XSL029)','I’ve been keeping a morning run log on the campus path, and it’s doing more for my brain than my pace. I’m not training for anything—just 15–25 minutes at an easy effort so it doesn’t wreck the rest of my day. The log is tiny: distance-ish, how I slept, and one sentence about how I felt after. Seeing patterns is motivating (turns out late-night snacks + running = regret). It’s the simplest routine I’ve actually repeated.',8,1,0,7,3,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(120,65,'Ten-minute stretching by the gym entrance (surprisingly effective) (XSL030)','Did my quick stretching routine near the gym entrance before heading back to the dorm, and it honestly made my day feel less stiff. I keep it low intensity: hips, calves, shoulders, and a slow cool-down so I’m not rushing straight into a shower and collapsing. The “prep” matters: water ready, towel ready, and I set a tiny timer so it doesn’t turn into scrolling. It’s not a full workout, but it’s a habit I can keep on busy class days.',8,1,0,0,3,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(121,60,'My weekend campus loop (timed + low-effort) (XSL031)','I kept telling myself I’d “remember” my weekend routine, and then every Saturday I wandered aimlessly and lost an hour. So I finally wrote down a simple loop that starts at the club activity room and ends back at my dorm: quick stop for printing, refill water, drop off recycling, and a short stretch break. Timing it made me realize where I always get stuck (spoiler: the crowded stairs). If you’re new to campus, keep it basic first—one repeatable route beats five random errands.',3,1,0,2,3,6,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(122,67,'A dorm-area walking route that actually clears my head (XSL032)','This week I started doing a short “reset walk” around the dorm buildings instead of doom-scrolling between classes. I mapped a loop that avoids the loudest intersections and hits the shady path behind the laundry room. It’s only about 18 minutes, but it’s long enough to calm down before studying. I also noted the best time to go (right after dinner rush is a mistake). Keeping a tiny routine like this feels way more realistic than trying to become a morning-run person overnight.',3,1,0,4,0,4,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:40',0),(123,55,'Track-style workout… in my dorm floor space (no gear) (XSL033)','I couldn’t make it to the track today, so I did a “track workout” in my dorm room: intervals on a yoga mat, high knees, mountain climbers, and a slow cooldown stretch. Nothing fancy, but it gets my heart rate up without needing equipment or a gym slot. The biggest lesson is planning the tiny stuff: water ready, towel within reach, and 10 minutes saved for cooling down so I don’t feel wrecked later. It’s not intense, just consistent—and that’s the point.',8,1,0,7,3,6,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(124,51,'A weekend lakeside route that stayed under budget (XSL034)','I did a low-cost weekend route along the lakeside path and it ended up cheaper than I expected. The trick was not packing the schedule too tight—when I left space to wander, I didn’t feel tempted to spend on random “convenience” purchases. I tracked the route, transit timing, and small costs (snacks, entry fees, etc.) so I can repeat it without overthinking. If you’re going with friends, pick one main stop and let the rest be flexible. It’s way more relaxing that way.',9,1,0,1,1,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(125,41,'Late-night snack near the library: worth it after studying (XSL035)','I finally tried the late-night snack spot by the library cafe, and it’s honestly a solid “post-study reward.” Price is student-friendly, portions are bigger than they look, and the wait wasn’t bad as long as you avoid the peak break between evening classes. I went with two friends and we split a couple items so it didn’t feel heavy. The best part is it’s close enough that you can grab it and head back without losing your study momentum. If you’re on a budget, share and skip the add-ons.',1,1,0,0,4,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(126,50,'20-minute rehearsal habit that saved my club week (XSL036)','Our club rehearsal schedule got chaotic, so I started doing a tiny 20-minute practice block in the quiet corner of the study room. I’m not chasing perfection—just keeping my hands and ears warmed up so rehearsal isn’t a panic. I grouped a few tracks by mood and tempo so I can switch between “focus” and “reset” without thinking. Writing down what worked (and what didn’t) helped more than I expected. If you’re busy, consistency beats long sessions you never actually do.',5,1,0,7,2,4,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(127,66,'Dorm smart device setup: mistakes I won’t repeat (XSL037)','I added a small “smart” setup to my dorm desk and learned a few things the hard way. With a student budget, start with the boring basics: stable power, a reliable hub, and one device that solves an everyday problem. I tried to get fancy too early and ended up troubleshooting instead of studying. After a week of tweaking, it’s finally stable—no random disconnects, no weird delays. If you’re setting up your own desk, prioritize fewer devices that you actually use daily, then expand later when it’s proven.',6,1,0,6,0,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(128,39,'One-day city walk starting at the park (easy pace) (XSL038)','I did a one-day city walk starting from the big park and it ended up being the perfect “mini reset” between assignments. I kept the route simple: park loop, riverside path, one museum stop, then a slow walk back through a quieter neighborhood. I wrote down the costs and transit steps so I can repeat it without last-minute stress. Biggest tip: don’t schedule every hour. Leaving room to wander made the whole day feel lighter, and I didn’t get that exhausted, overplanned feeling.',9,1,0,8,0,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(129,49,'Phone camera practice at the track bleachers (golden hour) (XSL039)','I’ve been practicing phone photos without over-editing, and today’s session at the track bleachers taught me a lot. The soft light near sunset made everything look calmer, so I focused on framing instead of filters: leading lines from the steps, a bit of negative space, and keeping the horizon steady. I only did light adjustments because I wanted the colors to stay close to what it felt like in person. Timing matters more than gear. If you’re learning, go out 20 minutes earlier than you think you need.',4,1,0,7,3,4,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(130,66,'Club-room route notes that make weekdays smoother (XSL040)','I keep underestimating how much tiny routines save my brain during busy weeks. This week I recorded a walking route that starts at the club activity room and loops past the places I always need: vending machines, the nearest quiet bench, and the shortcut back toward the dorms. It sounds silly, but knowing the timing means I stop arriving late and stressed. The “small details” add up—where the bottlenecks are, which doors get locked early, and which path stays less crowded. I’m keeping it as my default route for now.',3,1,0,2,0,6,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(131,61,'My 25-minute campus loop when my brain is stuck (XSL041)','I mapped out a simple walking loop that starts at the front of the teaching building and ends back near the library steps. It’s about 25 minutes at an easy pace, with two shaded stretches that feel surprisingly quiet even on busy days. I like it because there are no decisions: left at the fountain, straight past the small garden, then cut behind the lecture halls. I wrote the timing down so I can repeat it when I’m stressed and need a reset between classes.',3,1,0,6,4,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(132,46,'The cheapest hostel weekend that still felt safe (XSL042)','I did a one-night hostel stay this weekend and it ended up costing way less than I planned. The trick was booking a bed that’s slightly outside the tourist center and taking a direct bus from campus instead of multiple transfers. I kept the schedule loose: one museum, one long walk, and then just wandering for snacks. The hostel wasn’t fancy, but the common area was calm and the showers were clean. I wrote down my route and timing so I can copy-paste this trip during exam season.',9,1,0,2,2,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(133,68,'Spicy hotpot bowl review: east gate alley edition (XSL043)','Finally tried the spicy hotpot bowl place by the east gate alley and I get why people line up. It’s best with two or three friends so you can split add-ons and not feel like you overpaid for toppings. I went right after the rush and waited under 10 minutes, which honestly made the whole meal feel calmer. Flavor-wise: numbing spice first, then a deeper broth taste that sticks around. I jotted down price, wait time, and my topping combo so I can compare it with other spots later.',1,1,0,4,1,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(134,49,'My 20-minute guitar routine that actually sticks (XSL044)','I started keeping a tiny guitar practice log because I kept “practicing” in a way that was basically just noodling. My rule now: 20 minutes, same order every time. Five minutes warm-up, ten minutes rhythm work with a metronome, and five minutes of a song section I’m currently stuck on. I did a session near the track bleachers earlier and it felt weirdly peaceful with the wind and distant cheering. Not chasing flashy techniques yet—clean timing first. I’ll update if this routine survives finals.',5,1,0,0,1,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(135,44,'Noodle counter quick review for busy class days (XSL045)','Tried the noodle counter by the east gate alley again and this is my “between lectures” verdict. If you go during the peak break, you’ll wait forever and the seating gets chaotic. But outside the rush, it’s fast and honestly pretty satisfying for the price. The broth is lighter than it looks, so I recommend adding something with texture (mushrooms or tofu) to make it feel like a real meal. I wrote down what I ordered and how long it took so I don’t stand there thinking next time.',1,1,0,2,3,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(136,52,'Milk tea near the cafeteria: what I’d order again (XSL046)','There’s a new milk tea spot near the second-floor cafeteria and it’s actually student-budget friendly. I tried a classic milk tea with less sugar and added one topping, and it came out balanced instead of overly sweet. The line looked scary at first, but it moved faster than expected because they batch-prep a lot. If you’re rushing to a lab or club meeting, ordering ahead would help, but even walk-up wasn’t bad. I’m writing this down because I always forget which drink is worth it and end up panic-ordering something random.',1,1,0,1,4,1,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(137,55,'Finals review plan: fewer decisions, more pages done (XSL047)','I’m testing a finals review plan that’s basically designed for lazy brains (mine). Same study room, same start time, same first task every day so I don’t waste energy deciding. I keep one “done list” on the last page of my notebook and only write finished items there—no messy to-do list guilt. Today I did two short review blocks with a break in between, and it felt way more sustainable than cramming. If this keeps working, I’ll share a template for how I split topics without overplanning.',2,1,0,5,1,4,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(138,59,'Late-night playlist rules for when dorms are loud (XSL048)','I made a late-night listening list for those nights when the dorm is noisy but you still want your own quiet bubble. I grouped tracks by “soft focus,” “walking home,” and “lights out,” mostly based on tempo and how busy the instrumentation feels. The goal isn’t to find the coolest songs—it’s to make a predictable mood switch so my brain stops scrolling. I tested it sitting near the track bleachers after sunset and it was the perfect low-stimulation vibe. If you have any calm recommendations, I’m collecting them.',5,1,0,6,3,4,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:41',0),(139,62,'Tablet workflow that stopped my note-taking chaos (XSL049)','I finally have a tablet study workflow that feels stable instead of chaotic. My biggest mistake before was trying to use five apps and syncing everything perfectly—too much friction. Now I keep one folder per course, one template for lecture notes, and I only “pretty up” notes after I’ve actually understood the topic. I also learned to back up weekly instead of trusting auto-sync. I’ve been using this setup around the lab building between sessions, and it’s made quick review way easier. It’s not about specs; it’s about habits.',6,1,0,0,3,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(140,42,'Club rehearsal night: keeping it simple on purpose (XSL050)','Had a club rehearsal tonight and I’m reminding myself that “simple” is not the same as “boring.” We focused on rhythm and staying together instead of trying to add fancy fills, and it sounded cleaner immediately. I also started separating my practice playlists by purpose: one for warming up, one for learning, and one for decompressing after rehearsal so I don’t stay wired all night. The best part was packing up and realizing I wasn’t exhausted—just pleasantly tired. If your group is struggling, try stripping it back for a week.',5,1,0,3,4,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(141,58,'Dorm desk refresh that actually made studying easier (XSL051)','I finally did a small reset of my dorm desk after realizing I was constantly losing time to tiny annoyances. I moved the lamp to the left so my notebook doesn’t cast a shadow, tucked cables into clips, and made one “drop zone” tray for keys and earbuds. Nothing fancy, just a few practical swaps and a quick wipe-down. The best change: keeping only today’s materials on the surface. It feels calmer, and I’m weirdly more willing to sit down and start.',10,1,0,6,1,5,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(142,39,'Quiet guitar practice log for nights I can’t focus (XSL052)','I started keeping a tiny guitar practice log because my sessions kept turning into random noodling. Tonight was all about consistency: slow chord changes with a metronome, then a simple strumming pattern until it felt automatic. I wrote down what sounded clean vs. what buzzed, and it’s honestly helpful to see patterns (my ring finger is always the problem). I also made a small list of “comfort songs” for when I’m stressed, so practice still feels like a break.',5,1,0,7,4,0,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(143,46,'My no-stress campus walking loop (time-saving route) (XSL053)','For anyone still getting turned around on campus, here’s the walking loop I’ve settled into. I start near the dorms, cut behind the gym to avoid the crowded main stairs, then pass the quieter side entrance of the library before heading to the teaching buildings. It’s not the “shortest” on a map, but it’s smoother: fewer crosswalk waits, less bike traffic, and more shade. I’m sharing because it made my mornings less chaotic, especially on days with back-to-back classes.',3,1,0,2,1,9,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(144,63,'New milk tea spot: what to order and when to go (XSL054)','Tried the new milk tea place near the library cafe and it’s surprisingly student-budget friendly if you pick the right timing. The line gets wild right after the hour, so I went mid-afternoon and waited maybe five minutes. The drink itself was balanced (not overly sweet), and the ice didn’t melt into sadness immediately. If you’re going with friends, it’s a nice quick reset between study blocks. My only note: skip the extra toppings unless you really love chewy textures.',1,1,0,3,2,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(145,39,'Sticking to a morning run log finally paid off (XSL055)','I used to “run sometimes” which basically meant never. This week I kept a simple morning run log and it actually changed my motivation. I laid out shoes, socks, and a towel the night before, and promised myself the goal was just to show up. Once I started tracking how I felt after (energy, mood, focus), it got easier to repeat. I’m still slow and I’m not chasing distance yet, but the routine is becoming automatic. Next week I’ll add a short cooldown stretch plan.',8,1,0,3,4,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(146,55,'Monday class outfit: comfy, repeatable, not boring (XSL056)','Mondays are when I need my outfit to do the least and still look put-together. Today’s rule was “walkable and repeatable”: neutral top, relaxed pants, and shoes I can survive long hallways in. I’m trying to buy fewer pieces, so I’m testing whether one good basic can carry multiple looks with small changes (bag, jacket, jewelry). The biggest win is comfort—if I’m tugging at sleeves or adjusting straps all day, I can’t focus in class. Simple works.',7,1,0,5,0,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(147,68,'Got the rain reflection shot I’ve been chasing (XSL057)','It rained right before sunset, so the walkways turned into mirrors. I’ve tried taking reflection photos before, but they always looked flat. Today I crouched lower and framed the puddle so it caught both the building lights and the warm sky, and suddenly it worked. I kept edits minimal—just a tiny contrast boost—because the real scene already had that cinematic glow. Next time I want to experiment with motion blur from footsteps, but I’m happy I finally nailed the mood.',4,1,0,6,0,2,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(148,68,'Late-night listening list that doesn’t make me sleepy (XSL058)','I made a late-night listening list after realizing my “study music” was basically lullabies. The goal was steady energy without distracting vocals, so I sorted tracks by tempo and kept the vibe warm but not too dreamy. It’s been great for those activity-center nights when you’re waiting for laundry or finishing a last-minute slide deck. I also added a short “wind down” section at the end so I can stop doom-scrolling and actually go to bed. If you have recs, send them.',5,1,0,3,1,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(149,60,'This week’s guitar log: tiny progress, big relief (XSL059)','I’m noticing that guitar progress is mostly boring repetition, but it’s still progress. This week I did 20 minutes a day in the study room corner: chord transitions, clean fretting, and one song section on loop until it stopped falling apart. Keeping a log helped me stay honest, and it also made me kinder to myself—some days the win is just showing up. I’m not trying to be flashy; I just want my hands to feel steady. Next week I’ll record a short clip to compare.',5,1,0,4,2,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(150,57,'My low-effort weekly exercise plan for busy class weeks (XSL060)','I needed a weekly exercise plan that doesn’t collapse the moment assignments pile up. So I made a simple rotation: two short runs, one bodyweight session in the dorm, one long walk, and two “optional” days that can be stretching or nothing. The key is keeping it frictionless—no special equipment, no complicated splits, and everything fits into 20–40 minutes. I’m aiming for consistency over intensity, because that’s what actually survives midterms. If you’re starting from zero, this feels doable.',8,1,0,0,4,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(151,60,'My low-effort Monday outfit turned out surprisingly polished (XSL061)','I threw this on for my first class and honestly expected it to look too plain, but it ended up feeling put-together in a quiet way. My goal was: walkable, breathable, and not fussy when I’m rushing between buildings. Everything is something I already own, so it’s easy to remix later with older pieces. The best part is I didn’t spend the whole lecture tugging at sleeves or thinking about my shoes. I’m calling this a repeatable campus uniform.',7,1,0,7,1,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(152,66,'Dorm-entrance coffee corner: worth it on busy mornings? (XSL062)','I finally tried the little coffee corner by the dorm entrance and took notes like I’m my own food critic. The drink was smoother than I expected for the price, but the real win is the speed when you time it right. If you go during the exact class-change rush, you’ll wait and get annoyed. If you go five minutes earlier, it’s basically grab-and-go. It’s a good spot for two friends to meet before lecture, especially when you don’t want a full cafe trip.',1,1,0,5,2,4,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(153,64,'My no-stress campus walking loop (timed and repeatable) (XSL063)','I mapped out a simple walking loop from the dorm that doesn’t feel like “exercise,” but still gets me moving when I’m stuck in study mode all day. I picked paths that avoid the loudest intersections and added a quick detour past the convenience store so it feels useful. Total time is predictable, which is the whole point: I can do it between assignments without debating. If you’re new here, start with one loop and don’t overthink gear—comfortable shoes are enough.',3,1,0,2,1,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:42',0),(154,65,'My lab productivity setup: simple tools, less chaos (XSL064)','I’ve been tweaking my productivity setup in the lab and I think I finally found a balance that doesn’t collapse during a hectic week. I prioritized the boring basics: a clean file structure, one task list that I actually check, and a calendar that blocks time for experiments and write-ups. The surprise is how much stability comes from removing “extra” tools. Fewer tabs, fewer apps, fewer decisions. I’m still experimenting with shortcuts and templates, but this version feels reliable enough to recommend to anyone juggling labs and classes.',6,1,0,7,3,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(155,63,'Post-workout recovery that actually fits a class day (XSL065)','I used to skip recovery because it felt like “extra time,” but keeping it short has made it way easier to stick with. After a workout I do a quick cooldown walk, drink water, then spend a few minutes on simple stretches that don’t require any equipment. Nothing intense—just enough to stop my legs from feeling like bricks during afternoon lectures. The biggest change is consistency: a small routine I repeat beats a perfect routine I never do. If I keep noticing improvements, I’ll share a week-by-week update.',8,1,0,6,0,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(156,57,'Morning run notes: small prep, smoother day (XSL066)','Logged today’s morning run because I’m trying to make this a habit instead of a random burst of motivation. The trick that helps most: set out water and a towel the night before, then leave ten minutes for cooling down so I’m not rushing straight into a shower and class. I’m not chasing a fast pace—just steady effort and showing up. It’s simple, no fancy gear, and it weirdly makes the rest of the day feel more organized. If you’re starting, keep it easy and focus on finishing.',8,1,0,7,4,6,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(157,56,'Freshman packing list that stays practical (not overkill) (XSL067)','I keep seeing packing lists that look like you’re moving into a luxury apartment, so here’s my normal, comfortable version. Start with basics you’ll use every day: shower stuff, laundry bag, a small desk lamp, and one set of bedding that’s easy to wash. The tiny things matter more than you think—like a power strip and a couple of hooks—because they reduce daily friction. My rule is: don’t buy everything at once. Live here for a week, notice what annoys you, then fill the gaps.',10,1,0,0,1,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(158,67,'Guitar practice log: rhythm first, ego later (XSL068)','I started a new guitar practice log in the club room because my sessions were getting messy—lots of noodling, not much progress. This week I grouped what I’m working on by mood and tempo, so I can switch between “focus” and “fun” without spiraling. I’m intentionally keeping technique simple: clean chord changes, steady strumming, and timing with a metronome. It’s not flashy, but it’s the kind of boring consistency that actually improves your playing. If anyone wants, I can share my weekly structure.',5,1,0,2,0,4,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(159,61,'Choosing a student laptop: what mattered after the specs (XSL069)','I’ve been helping a friend pick a laptop, so I wrote down what actually matters once you stop staring at spec sheets. For student life, stability and battery behavior are huge—especially if you bounce between lab, library, and random hallway outlets. I also care about how it handles real multitasking: browser tabs, documents, and coding tools without turning into a space heater. The “best” choice depends on your workload, but I’m convinced that a reliable mid-range setup beats an impressive list of numbers that’s annoying to use daily.',6,1,0,0,0,6,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(160,55,'Library-window light is my new favorite photo hack (XSL070)','I practiced phone photography by the library window and finally got the look I’ve been chasing: soft light, gentle shadows, and a frame that feels layered instead of flat. The biggest change was lowering my viewpoint so the foreground had something to “lead” your eye. Also, timing is everything—ten minutes earlier or later and the light goes harsh. I’m trying to rely less on editing and more on getting it right in-camera. If you’re learning too, start with one window and test angles before touching filters.',4,1,0,0,0,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(161,50,'Dorm-Friendly Stretching That Actually Sticks (XSL071)','I’ve been trying to stop the “sit all day, regret it at night” cycle, so I made a tiny stretching routine I can do right in my dorm before I head to the running path. It’s 8–10 minutes, no equipment, and it doesn’t make me sweaty enough to need a full shower. I start with ankles/hips (because stairs), then shoulders/neck (because laptop), and finish with slow breathing. The biggest surprise: doing less, consistently, feels way better than random intense sessions.',8,1,0,3,4,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:50',0),(162,43,'Rainy-Day Reflections by the Lake Bench (XSL072)','It finally rained at the perfect time, so I went back to the lake bench to chase that mirror-like reflection I always miss. The trick (for me) was getting low enough that the puddle became the “foreground frame,” then waiting for a tiny break in the wind so the water would settle. I kept edits minimal—just a little contrast—because the real scene already had that soft, washed look. It’s funny how a quiet campus can feel cinematic when everything is wet and glowing.',4,1,0,8,4,5,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(163,58,'Track-Day Cooldown I Won’t Skip Anymore (XSL073)','After running intervals at the school track, I used to just grab water and disappear. Today I forced myself to do a real cooldown and it honestly changed how my legs felt walking back to the dorm. I did a slow lap, then a simple sequence: calves against the curb, hamstring stretch, hip flexor lunge, and a gentle quad stretch. Nothing dramatic, just steady breathing and not rushing it. My goal is to keep it boring and repeatable so it survives midterm season.',8,1,0,3,1,6,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(164,52,'My “Not Too Formal” Interview Outfit Formula (XSL074)','I put together an interview outfit that doesn’t feel like a costume, and I’m kind of relieved. The goal was: clean lines, comfortable shoes, and pieces I’ll rewear for presentations and dinners with friends. I went with neutral colors, a structured top layer, and pants that don’t wrinkle the second I sit down in a lecture hall. The best part is everything mixes with stuff I already own, so it doesn’t scream “new interview clothes.” If you’re building from scratch, start with one reliable outer layer.',2,1,0,1,1,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(165,55,'Sunset by the Lake Bench Felt Like a Reset (XSL075)','I walked past the lake after a long day and the sunset basically told me to slow down. The colors were warm but not dramatic—more like everything got softened around the edges. I took a few shots from different heights and the lower angle made the water look deeper and calmer. I didn’t do heavy edits because I wanted it to stay close to what it felt like in person: quiet, a little windy, and weirdly comforting. If you’re stressed, try a five-minute detour before going back to your room.',4,1,0,8,4,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(166,51,'My Tablet + Laptop Workflow Test at the Library (XSL076)','I tried a new library setup today: tablet for reading and annotating, laptop for writing and coding, and a super basic checklist so I don’t spend 20 minutes rearranging things. I’m not chasing the “perfect” gear—just trying to reduce friction. What worked: keeping the tablet slightly angled for quick glance notes, and using a single folder for today’s files so I don’t lose them later. What didn’t: too many open apps. Next time I’m limiting it to one note page, one reference, one draft.',2,1,0,4,1,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(167,50,'Interview Outfit Photos So I Can Recreate It Fast (XSL077)','I took quick photos of today’s interview outfit because I always forget what worked once the week gets busy. The main idea is repeatable basics: one structured layer, one simple top, and shoes I can actually walk across campus in. I’m trying to build a tiny “uniform” that looks put-together without feeling stiff. Also: pockets matter more than I used to admit. Next step is making two variations—one warmer, one lighter—so I’m not panicking the night before. If you have a go-to combo, share it.',7,1,0,5,1,4,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(168,56,'Guitar Practice: Small Wins, No Heroics (XSL078)','This week’s guitar practice finally felt less chaotic. Instead of chasing flashy techniques, I kept it boring: slow rhythm drills, clean chord changes, and a metronome pace I could actually hold. I also started grouping songs by mood—one “focus” set for study breaks and one “decompress” set for late nights—so I’m not picking randomly when my brain is tired. Writing a short log helped more than I expected because it shows patterns (like how I always rush the same transition). Next week: same plan, just slightly faster.',5,1,0,3,2,2,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(169,44,'An Interview Outfit That Survives Walking to Class (XSL079)','I tested an interview outfit on a regular campus day because I wanted to know if it’s actually wearable, not just “looks good standing still.” The big rules: nothing that pinches when you sit, shoes that don’t punish you on stairs, and colors that stay calm in different lighting. I kept it simple and neat, and it still felt like me. If I could only recommend one thing, it’s choosing a top layer that instantly makes everything look intentional. Bonus: it also works for presentations and office hours.',7,1,0,2,2,5,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(170,50,'My Low-Stress Vocabulary Routine for Busy Weeks (XSL080)','I’ve been trying to make vocabulary practice feel less like punishment, so I built a calmer routine in the department study room. Same seat, same time window, and one tiny goal: finish a short set and stop. The biggest improvement is reducing decisions—everything I need is already in one place, and I write the “done list” on the last page so tomorrow starts with a quick win. It’s not fancy, but it keeps me consistent when deadlines stack up. If you’re stuck, try shrinking the task until it’s almost too easy to skip.',2,1,0,6,0,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(171,53,'Midnight bleachers playlist that actually calms my brain (XSL081)','I ended up by the track bleachers again after a long day, just trying to decompress without scrolling myself into oblivion. I made a small late-night listening list: soft indie, a little lo-fi, and two acoustic tracks that feel like a deep breath. No fancy “music theory” goal tonight—just steady rhythm and a mood I can sit with. Twenty minutes of quiet listening is weirdly enough to reset me before sleep. If I tweak it later, I’ll share a version for rainy nights too.',5,1,0,4,2,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(172,57,'My finals plan is boring on purpose, and it works (XSL082)','I finally stopped making “perfect” revision schedules and wrote a plan I can repeat without negotiating with myself. Same time, same seat, same first task: 10 minutes of review questions before I open any notes. I keep a tiny list of finished items on the last page so tomorrow starts with momentum instead of guilt. Also: I pre-pack highlighters, tabs, and a snack so I don’t wander off. It’s not glamorous, but my brain feels calmer walking into the teaching building now.',2,1,0,2,1,5,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(173,49,'Logging my morning runs made me way less dramatic about them (XSL083)','I started a simple morning run log and it’s honestly changing how I think about “fitness.” No hero distances—just showing up. I set out a towel and a water bottle the night before, then I give myself a real cool-down window so I’m not sprinting into class sweaty and annoyed. The log is mostly notes like: how my legs felt, what time I went, and whether I slept enough. Seeing patterns is the motivation. Turns out consistency is easier than hype.',8,1,0,7,3,1,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(174,55,'The packing list I wish someone handed me on day one (XSL084)','I wrote down a freshman packing list after watching people struggle at the track field this week (you can tell who just moved in). Tiny things make campus life smoother: a small laundry bag, a long charging cable, a cheap umbrella, and a spare tote for grocery runs. Also: bring fewer “decor” items and more boring basics like hooks and a mini first-aid kit. I even noted the best times to hit the campus store so you don’t queue forever. Hope this saves someone stress.',3,1,0,2,4,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(175,55,'South gate milk tea: what I’d order again (and what I wouldn’t) (XSL085)','Tried the new milk tea spot near the south gate after class and took notes like the nerd I am. The wait was about a song-and-a-half if you go right at the end of a lecture block, but it gets packed fast. I ordered a classic milk tea with less sugar and it was smooth, not overly perfumed. Price felt fair for a student treat, but I wouldn’t go every day. Best move is splitting a couple drinks with friends so you can sample without draining your wallet.',1,1,0,3,3,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(176,64,'A low-effort track run that I can repeat on busy days (XSL086)','Did my usual morning loop at the school track and kept it intentionally easy. I’m trying to build a routine that survives weeks with labs and group meetings, so the goal is “finish feeling okay,” not “destroy myself.” I pack water and a towel beforehand, and I force a 10-minute cool-down walk so my heart rate actually comes down. Writing the run down right after helps too—otherwise every day feels the same and I forget what’s working. Simple beats perfect.',8,1,0,3,0,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(177,44,'South gate noodles: fast, filling, and surprisingly not greasy (XSL087)','I grabbed noodles at the counter near the south gate and I’m kind of impressed. Portions are generous for the price, and it’s one of the few places where I don’t feel like I need a nap afterward. Biggest tip: go with two or three friends and aim for a weird time (like 20 minutes after the rush) because the line moves slowly when everyone shows up at once. Flavor is solid, spice level is adjustable, and the whole thing feels very “student survival” in a good way.',1,1,0,3,4,1,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:51',0),(178,44,'Dorm desk refresh: the 20-minute reset that saved my week (XSL088)','My desk was turning into a paper landfill, so I did a quick refresh and wrote down what helped. I started with the boring stuff: throw out packaging, stack loose papers into one folder, wipe the surface, then set up a “today only” tray so I stop spreading tasks everywhere. I also moved my charger to one fixed spot because I lose it daily. If you’re a freshman, don’t buy ten organizers at once—use one box first and see what you actually reach for.',10,1,0,6,2,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(179,41,'My tablet study workflow (what helps, what’s overrated) (XSL089)','I’ve been using a tablet for studying in the teaching building lounge and I finally have a workflow that feels stable. I keep one notebook for rough thinking, and the tablet is for clean summaries and diagrams—otherwise I get lost in endless “organizing.” Biggest money-saving advice: cover the common scenarios first (PDFs, lecture slides, problem sets) before buying accessories. Also, don’t rely on fancy apps; the habit matters more. If I change anything next week, it’ll be setting stricter offline time.',6,1,0,0,3,5,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(180,67,'Spicy hotpot bowl review: worth it, but choose your add-ons wisely (XSL090)','Tried the spicy hotpot bowl near the south gate and wrote down the details because my memory is unreliable when I’m hungry. The base broth is flavorful and actually spicy, not just oily. Price is okay if you don’t go wild with add-ons—those sneak up fast. Waiting time is decent unless you hit the exact class break. Best strategy is going with friends, sharing a couple sides, and skipping the extra noodles unless you’re starving. I’d get it again on a cold day for sure.',1,1,0,1,4,3,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(181,43,'Budget fall layers I keep repeating by the study room doors (XSL091)','I snapped this outfit right by the study room entrance because the lighting there is oddly perfect. I’m trying to build a tiny “repeatable” closet this semester, so everything here is comfortable, re-wearable, and easy to mix with older pieces. My rule: neutral base, one texture, and shoes I can actually walk across campus in. The best part is I didn’t buy anything new for this—just re-styled what I already had. Next time I’ll post a rainy-day version too.',7,1,0,3,3,0,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(182,57,'Noodle counter notes: what to order and when to go (XSL092)','Tried the noodle counter near the library cafe again and finally wrote down the details like a responsible adult. Prices are student-friendly and the portion is bigger than it looks from the menu board. The line moves fast unless you hit the 10-minute class break rush, then it’s chaos. If you’re going with friends, it’s easiest to grab a table first and rotate ordering. Flavor-wise: go for something broth-based if you’re studying after—less greasy, less regret. I’ll test a spicy option next week.',1,1,0,5,1,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(183,44,'My tablet workflow that stopped my note-taking chaos (XSL093)','I’ve been using a tablet + laptop workflow near the lab building and it finally feels stable instead of “new gadget energy.” The biggest mistake I made early on was trying to do everything in one app. Now I separate tasks: handwritten lecture notes on the tablet, readings and PDFs on the laptop, and a simple folder system that mirrors my course weeks. I also keep one charging cable permanently in my backpack so I’m not gambling with battery life. It’s not fancy, but it’s consistent—and consistency is the real upgrade.',6,1,0,7,1,1,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(184,45,'Laptop choice lessons from actually using it in the library (XSL094)','I used to shop laptops like it was a spec sheet competition, but daily campus life is way more boring (and more important). What ended up mattering most for me: battery that lasts a long afternoon, a keyboard that doesn’t make my hands angry, and a screen that’s readable under library lights. I also underestimated how much I’d carry it—weight becomes very real after a week. If you’re choosing right now, borrow a friend’s for 10 minutes and type a paragraph. That test is brutally honest.',6,1,0,3,0,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(185,43,'Rain reflections by the track bleachers felt like a pause button (XSL095)','After the rain, the track area got weirdly quiet and the puddles turned into little mirrors. I kept the camera low and let the reflection take up more space than the actual bleachers, and it instantly felt calmer. The soft light right before sunset helped a lot—everything looked less harsh, more layered. I also learned that waiting two minutes matters; the wind dies down and the surface smooths out. This was one of those moments where campus feels like a different place for a second.',4,1,0,4,4,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(186,64,'The only study room schedule I’ve managed to keep (XSL096)','I finally made a study room schedule that doesn’t collapse the second life gets busy. The trick is honestly boring: I go at the same time on the same days, so I don’t waste energy negotiating with myself. I work in short blocks (25–30 minutes) and only write down the next tiny step, not a giant to-do list that scares me off. If I finish early, I use the extra time to set up tomorrow’s materials. It’s not intense, but it’s sustainable—and that’s what I needed.',2,1,0,0,4,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(187,55,'Laptop buying mistakes I won’t repeat in a dorm setup (XSL097)','I’ve watched too many friends panic-buy laptops right before projects are due, so here’s what I learned from setting mine up at the dorm desk. Prioritize what you actually do most days: writing, slides, coding, or design work. Then think about the boring parts—ports, charging, fan noise, and whether the screen is comfortable for long sessions. I also recommend budgeting for a basic stand and a cheap mouse; they make a bigger difference than a slightly faster processor. I’ll update after midterms when stress testing is real.',6,1,0,5,2,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(188,55,'Cafe window seat schedule that makes studying feel doable (XSL098)','I’ve been using the cafe window seat as my “default” study spot, and having a routine there makes starting way easier. I plan in blocks: one block for reading, one for practice problems, one for quick review, and I stop before I’m completely fried. The biggest change is I decide the night before what the first task is, so I don’t sit down and scroll for ten minutes. If you’re struggling with consistency, pick a time and location you can repeat, even if it’s not perfect.',2,1,0,5,0,0,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(189,55,'Library cafe coffee corner: quick review for post-class cravings (XSL099)','Stopped by the coffee corner near the library cafe after class because I needed something warm and I didn’t want a full meal. It’s one of those places that’s “fine” in the best way: affordable, fast, and consistent. I wrote down the wait time and what I ordered because I always forget which drink is too sweet for me. Pro tip: go five minutes before the rush, not during it. I like pairing it with a short reading session so it feels like a reset instead of procrastination.',1,1,0,7,0,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(190,60,'Freshman packing list that keeps dorm life simple (XSL100)','If I could redo freshman move-in, I’d pack fewer “cute” things and more practical basics. A small set of storage bins, a power strip with enough outlets, shower sandals, and a laundry bag that actually holds a week’s clothes will save you so much friction. For studying, one desk lamp with warm light and a simple organizer beats buying random stationery you’ll never touch. Also: bring one comfort item (blanket, pillow, or photo) because dorms can feel sterile at first. I’ll add a winter update later.',3,1,0,8,0,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(191,47,'My no-stress interview outfit by the teaching building lobby (XSL101)','I had a quick interview prep meeting today, so I snapped my outfit in the teaching building lobby while I still felt put together. I’m trying to build a tiny “repeatable” wardrobe: one blazer that doesn’t wrinkle easily, a soft knit top that doesn’t itch, and trousers I can actually climb stairs in. Neutral colors make it easy to mix with older pieces, and comfy shoes are non-negotiable. The best part is everything works for class days too, not just interview days.',7,1,0,4,3,4,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(192,52,'Rehearsal felt less chaotic this week (finally) (XSL102)','Our club rehearsal near the track bleachers was weirdly productive today. We’re still not “good,” but we’re tighter than last week, which is honestly all I want. I started doing 20-minute daily drills instead of one long panic practice, and it’s paying off. I also reorganized my set list by energy level so I’m not trying to learn fast parts when my brain is fried. Small win: I didn’t get lost in the bridge once. I’ll take it.',5,1,0,4,1,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:33:52',0),(193,44,'Milk tea by the library: worth the line? (XSL103)','I finally tried the new milk tea spot next to the library cafe because everyone kept hyping it up. The price is student-friendly and the cup is bigger than I expected. I went right after class break and waited about 10 minutes, which isn’t terrible, but I wouldn’t try it during peak rush. Flavor-wise: not overly sweet, and the tea actually tastes like tea. It’s a good “study reward” drink if you’re with two or three friends and want a quick sit-down.',1,1,0,5,1,5,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(194,50,'Late-night playlist for when the dorm is too loud (XSL104)','I made a late-night listening list for those nights when the dorm is loud but I still need to finish something. I grouped songs by tempo instead of genre, so I can switch from “focus” to “cool down” without thinking. The rule I’m trying: no super catchy hooks during reading, then a few brighter tracks when I’m doing mindless tasks like formatting. It sounds small, but it helps me stop doom-scrolling between paragraphs. If you have calm recs, please drop them.',5,1,0,3,2,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(195,42,'Prepping for the activity center set without overthinking (XSL105)','I practiced at the activity center today and tried a new approach: stop chasing fancy technique and just lock in rhythm. I’m the type who spirals if one chord buzzes, so I set a timer for 20 minutes and focused on clean transitions instead. It’s boring, but it works. I also wrote a tiny checklist for performance day (strings, pick, water, backup capo) because I always forget something when I’m nervous. Feeling a little more steady now.',5,1,0,7,0,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(196,51,'Monday outfit that survives rain and long lectures (XSL106)','Monday was one of those days: back-to-back classes, surprise drizzle, and a last-minute study room session. I wore my “low effort, high comfort” combo and it actually held up. The key was choosing one basic layer that repeats well (a simple jacket) and keeping everything else neutral so I didn’t have to think. I’m also officially done wearing shoes that look cute but hurt by noon. If you’re building a campus wardrobe, start with pieces you can walk fast in.',7,1,0,2,1,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(197,52,'Unexpectedly wearable Monday look from my closet corner (XSL107)','I threw this Monday outfit together in the closet corner and expected it to feel “meh,” but it ended up being super wearable. I’m trying to buy less and re-wear more, so I’m testing whether each piece can match at least three older items. The vibe I’m aiming for is clean and quiet: nothing loud, nothing fussy, just comfortable and easy to move in. Also, pockets matter more than trends. I’ll probably repeat this combo on presentation days too.',7,1,0,1,2,4,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(198,67,'My 10-minute dorm stretch that actually sticks (XSL108)','I’ve been stiff from sitting all day, so I wrote down a super simple dorm stretching routine that doesn’t require equipment or motivation. It’s low intensity: neck rolls, shoulder openers, hip flexor stretch, hamstring fold, then a minute of breathing to reset. The main goal is consistency, not “burn.” I do it right after brushing my teeth so it becomes automatic, and it doesn’t mess up the rest of my schedule. If you’re sore from studying, try it for a week.',8,1,0,0,2,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(199,60,'Tiny desk refresh that made studying feel easier (XSL109)','I did a small desk refresh in the dorm and it made my whole week feel less messy. Nothing fancy: I cleared the random flyers, moved my lamp to reduce glare, and set up one “drop zone” tray for keys and earbuds so I stop losing them. I also timed my usual morning routine and realized I waste five minutes hunting for stuff. The changes are small, but they make campus life smoother. If your desk feels chaotic, start by removing just one category of clutter.',10,1,0,6,2,4,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(200,62,'Quiet practice session in the music club room (XSL110)','I had the music club room to myself for a bit, so I did a calm performance prep session instead of my usual frantic run-through. I focused on rhythm stability and keeping my hands relaxed, because that’s what falls apart when I’m nervous. Twenty minutes of slow practice honestly did more than an hour of rushing. I also recorded a quick voice memo after each run to note what tripped me up, since I forget the moment I leave the room. Slow progress, but real progress.',5,1,0,4,0,2,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:00',0),(201,51,'Window-seat notes template that actually keeps me on track (XSL111)','I parked myself at the cafe window seat and tried a new digital notes template I built for this week’s reading. The biggest change wasn’t the layout—it was how it forced me to start with one tiny block instead of a giant to-do list. I set a 25-minute timer, wrote just three questions I needed to answer, and only then opened the article. Fewer choices = less stalling. By the end I had a clean summary and a short “next time” list instead of messy half-notes.',2,1,0,6,0,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(202,61,'Late-night listening list from the club room, zero skips (XSL112)','After rehearsal I stayed in the music club room for ten minutes and made a late-night listening list for the walk back to my dorm. I’m trying to be more intentional: fewer tracks, more repeats, and a clear purpose. I sorted it into three mini sections—warm-up (steady rhythm), focus (simple harmonies), and unwind (slow, roomy sounds). It’s kind of boring in the best way, because it keeps my brain from spiraling into doom-scrolling. Twenty minutes a day really does add up.',5,1,0,0,1,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(203,64,'Library-seat coding setup: simple, stable, and not fancy (XSL113)','I tested my programming project setup from a quiet library seat today and I’m relieved it held up. My rule this semester is “cover the common case first”: clean folder structure, one script to run everything, and a backup plan if the campus Wi‑Fi decides to be dramatic. I kept the setup minimal—laptop + tablet for docs—and focused on stability over aesthetics. The best part is I can pack it in two minutes when I need to move. Next time I’ll measure battery drain properly.',6,1,0,1,2,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(204,63,'My boring morning run log is working, annoyingly (XSL114)','I started keeping a super basic morning run log on the campus path and it’s actually changing my habits. Nothing intense: short warm-up, easy pace, and a note about how my legs felt. The “log” part is the key—if I write it down right after, I’m way less likely to skip the next day because I can see the pattern. I also plan the smallest details the night before (socks, keys, water), which removes all the morning excuses. It’s boring, but it’s consistent.',8,1,0,1,1,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(205,57,'Late-night playlist for the study room corner mood (XSL115)','I made a late-night listening list while camped in the study room corner, and it’s oddly calming. I split it by mood instead of genre: “keep typing,” “pause and think,” and “lights-out.” The point isn’t being sophisticated; it’s giving my brain a predictable soundtrack so I don’t start chasing novelty every five minutes. I’m also trying a rule where I don’t add new songs after midnight—only rearrange what’s already there. Somehow that makes it feel like a routine instead of a rabbit hole.',5,1,0,0,0,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(206,41,'Guitar practice log that fits into a chaotic week (XSL116)','I started a guitar practice log in the club room because I kept “practicing” without actually improving anything. My new rule is 20 minutes, one focus: either clean chord changes, rhythm accuracy, or dynamics. I write one sentence about what felt hard and one sentence about what felt easier than last time. That’s it. No huge goals, no fancy plan. It’s surprisingly motivating to see a string of small wins instead of one dramatic session every two weeks. Also: metronome at a slower tempo is humbling.',5,1,0,3,1,4,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(207,44,'Finals review plan that doesn’t self-destruct by day three (XSL117)','I finally made a finals review plan I can keep using without burning out. The trick is embarrassingly simple: same room, same start time, and one pre-chosen task for the first 10 minutes. I break everything into small “passes” (skim notes, do a few practice questions, then check mistakes). If I finish early, I stop anyway and save the momentum for tomorrow. It feels less like cramming and more like maintenance. I’m also leaving one buffer day per week because life happens and professors love surprise assignments.',2,1,0,7,4,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(208,43,'The campus sunset shot I’ve been chasing all semester (XSL118)','I finally got the campus sunset photo I’ve been trying to catch since the first week of classes. I shot it from the library window when the light softened and everything turned that warm peach color for about five minutes. I kept edits super light because the real scene was already doing the work—just a tiny lift in shadows and a bit less contrast so it still feels gentle. The main lesson: timing beats gear every time. Also, cleaning the camera lens before you start is the most unglamorous win.',4,1,0,8,2,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(209,56,'Dorm stretching routine that doesn’t need motivation (XSL119)','I’ve been doing a super student-friendly stretching routine and it’s helping more than I expected. I keep it short: five minutes of gentle mobility after waking up, then a slightly longer stretch after the gym or a long lab day. The secret is setting everything up first—water bottle filled, towel ready, shoes by the door—so it feels automatic. I’m not aiming for extreme flexibility, just less stiffness from sitting in lectures. Ten minutes of cooldown makes the rest of the evening feel less tense, especially after computer-heavy days.',8,1,0,8,1,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(210,68,'Quiet-time study playlist for when I need to be alone (XSL120)','I made a study playlist for the kind of quiet time where you’re alone but not lonely—just trying to get through your tasks without extra noise in your head. I tested it while sitting near the track bleachers after class, and it was the perfect “reset” before heading back to my desk. The playlist is mostly steady tempos and soft textures, nothing with big surprise moments. I like having a clear boundary: headphones on = focus mode, headphones off = real break. It sounds small, but it keeps my day from blending together.',5,1,0,2,3,7,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(211,41,'Dorm Desk Rehearsal Notes That Actually Helped (XSL121)','I practiced for the campus performance again tonight, squeezed between laundry and a last-minute reading. I used to brute-force the hard parts, but I finally tried something calmer: 20 minutes, timer on, and only clean transitions. I also sorted the set list by energy level so I’m not jumping from a slow ballad straight into fast strumming. It’s not perfect, but the rhythm stayed steady longer than usual. If we run it again this weekend, I’ll update with what worked on stage.',5,1,0,4,4,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(212,48,'Hostel Stay Tips for a Broke Student Weekend (XSL122)','Quick notes from my hostel stay near the park: the biggest win was not over-scheduling. I left two open blocks to just wander, grab coffee, and sit by the water without staring at maps. Booking the bed and train a week early saved more than I expected, and I ate mostly at tiny family-run places (cheap, filling, and honestly better). The hostel itself was basic but clean, and having a shared kitchen made breakfast almost free. Next time I’m packing earplugs first.',9,1,0,2,2,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(213,67,'A Study Playlist That Kept Me From Doom-Scrolling (XSL123)','I rebuilt my study playlist while waiting outside the activity center, and it’s weirdly made my evenings calmer. Instead of chasing “impressive” songs, I picked tracks that keep a steady pulse and don’t yank my attention around. I split it into two sections: low-key background for reading, and slightly brighter stuff for problem sets when I need momentum. The test run was good—no urge to skip every 30 seconds. If it still works during midterms, I’ll share the full structure and timing.',5,1,0,0,0,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(214,54,'My Simple Rehearsal Plan for Busy Weeks (XSL124)','I wrote a mini rehearsal plan at my dorm desk because I kept losing track of what I practiced. The goal isn’t perfection—it’s showing up every day even when classes are heavy. I’m focusing on rhythm and stability first: slow strums, clean chord changes, and only speeding up if it stays smooth. I also made a tiny checklist for warmup so I don’t waste the first five minutes “getting ready.” It feels realistic for student life, and I can actually stick to it without burning out.',5,1,0,4,0,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(215,57,'Quiet Ginkgo Path + Rain Reflections on Campus (XSL125)','I walked past the ginkgo path by the lake bench right after a light rain, and it felt like the whole campus got turned down to a whisper. The reflections on the walkway were doing all the work, so I tried to keep the shot simple—straight lines, a little negative space, and no heavy edits. Softer light made the yellow leaves look more natural instead of neon. I’m still learning to stop over-processing everything. This one is basically “what it looked like,” and I like it more that way.',4,1,0,7,3,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(216,40,'East Gate Milk Tea: Worth the Wait or Nah? (XSL126)','Tried the new milk tea spot in the east gate alley because everyone in my class kept mentioning it. Price was student-friendly and the portion was bigger than I expected. The line looked scary at first, but it moved fast—maybe 10 minutes total. Flavor-wise, it was balanced and not overly sweet, which I appreciate when I’m heading back to study. I jotted down the cost, sweetness level, and wait time so I can compare it with other places near campus. Next time I’m trying a fruit tea.',1,1,0,8,3,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:01',0),(217,68,'Freshman Packing List: What I’d Actually Bring Again (XSL127)','I finally organized a packing list for freshmen because I watched my roommate panic-buy random stuff last year. The basics matter more than the “cute extras”: a small power strip, a laundry bag, shower sandals, and one decent hoodie for late-night library runs. I also wrote down the first-day route from the dorm to the teaching building so you’re not wandering with luggage. Tiny details, but they make the first week less chaotic. If you have a must-have item I missed, drop it below and I’ll update it.',3,1,0,6,0,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(218,48,'Music Club Room Session: Tracking Progress Without Stress (XSL128)','I started a guitar practice log in the music club room because my memory is basically a sieve during busy weeks. Instead of grinding flashy techniques, I’m prioritizing rhythm and consistency—if the groove is shaky, everything else falls apart. I also grouped the songs I’m learning by vibe and tempo, so I can pick something that matches my energy after class. The log is simple: what I played, what sounded messy, and one tiny goal for tomorrow. It’s surprisingly motivating to see small wins add up.',5,1,0,7,2,4,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(219,47,'My Weekend Trip Budget Breakdown That Stayed Under Control (XSL129)','I wrote up a student-budget weekend trip guide because I’m tired of coming home and pretending I didn’t spend money. The main trick was locking in transport and a cheap stay early, then building the route around walkable areas instead of hopping across the city all day. I kept meals simple: local spots with short menus, one “nice” snack, and grocery breakfast. I tracked costs in notes as I went, and it honestly reduced the stress. If anyone wants, I can share a template for planning routes and spending caps.',9,1,0,5,0,6,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(220,58,'Freshman Packing List: Don’t Overbuy on Day One (XSL130)','Posting this for incoming students: please don’t buy everything at once just because the student center shops are right there. Start with basics for sleeping, showering, and studying, then add things after you learn your room setup. I made a short list plus a “first weekend” reminder: check what your roommates already brought (kettle, cleaning stuff, extra hangers) so you’re not duplicating. I also wrote down a simple route for errands so you’re not zig-zagging across campus in the heat. I’ll update after orientation week.',3,1,1,6,1,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(221,51,'Dorm mirror check: thrifted fall layers that look polished (XSL131)','I did a quick mirror photo by my closet corner before running to class, because I keep forgetting what actually works on busy mornings. Today’s vibe was quiet and practical: soft knit, straight-leg pants, and sneakers I can walk across campus in without thinking. Everything is either thrifted or a basic I’ve worn a hundred times, which honestly is the goal. If I could only keep one thing from this outfit, it’d be the neutral outer layer—it makes everything else look intentional.',7,1,0,2,2,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(222,54,'My dorm desk setup for a late-night coding demo (XSL132)','I’m testing my programming class project setup at my dorm desk because demo day is coming fast. I finally got it stable enough that it doesn’t randomly disconnect when I bump the table (huge win). The trick was keeping the wires shorter, taping down the loose parts, and writing a tiny checklist in my notebook so I don’t forget steps when I’m tired. If you’re on a student budget, prioritize reliability first—extra gadgets are fun, but a clean setup saves hours.',6,1,0,5,1,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(223,67,'Rehearsal felt less chaotic after one small change (XSL133)','Club rehearsal this week was at the bleachers again, and for once it felt like we were actually locking in. I stopped chasing fancy technique and just focused on steady rhythm and clean transitions. It’s kind of boring advice, but it worked: slow it down, repeat the hard eight bars, then run the whole thing once without stopping. Twenty minutes a day adds up more than one long panic practice. I’m going to keep the same routine next week and see if it sticks.',5,1,0,7,2,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(224,62,'Five-minute dorm stretches that made my back feel normal again (XSL134)','I’ve been doing a super simple stretching routine between classes and it’s honestly the first “fitness” habit that hasn’t annoyed me. No equipment, no intensity, just consistency: hamstrings, hip flexors, shoulders, and a slow twist on the floor. I started because my lower back was getting stiff from sitting all day, and after a week it felt noticeably better. The best part is it doesn’t require motivation—just set a timer and do it before your brain negotiates.',8,1,0,4,2,0,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(225,66,'What I learned building my class project at the library (XSL135)','I worked on my programming class project at the library today and realized how different “works at my dorm” is from “works anywhere.” The quiet helped, but the real difference was space: I could lay everything out, label what goes where, and stop yanking wires around. I’m trying to judge my setup by daily usability, not specs—can I pack it, set it up fast, and debug without losing my mind? Next step is making a small kit so I can move locations easily.',6,1,0,2,1,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(226,44,'A finals plan that doesn’t collapse after day two (XSL136)','I finally made a finals review plan that I can actually follow without burning out. The key is boring consistency: same cafe window seat, same start time, and a short list that fits in one sitting. I split everything into 25–30 minute blocks and I stop while I still have energy, which makes it easier to come back tomorrow. I also keep a “done” page at the back so I can see progress when my brain insists I’m behind. It’s simple, but it feels doable.',2,1,0,1,2,2,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(227,46,'Morning runs got easier once I started tracking one thing (XSL137)','I’ve been keeping a tiny morning run log and it’s making the whole habit feel less random. I don’t track everything—just distance and how my legs felt, because that’s enough to spot patterns. The biggest help is prepping the night before: shoes by the door, water ready, and a towel waiting so I’m not scrambling. I leave ten minutes for cooling down and stretching so I don’t limp into my first lecture. It’s not dramatic progress, but it’s steady, and I’ll take that.',8,1,0,0,3,1,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(228,68,'Laptop buying mistakes I skipped (and one I didn’t) (XSL138)','I’ve been using my current laptop for a while now, and I’m relieved I avoided a few rookie mistakes when I bought it. I didn’t chase the thinnest model or the fanciest specs—I focused on whether it stays cool during long study sessions and whether the battery survives a day of classes. What I didn’t anticipate: how much I’d care about the keyboard feel when writing labs and essays back-to-back. If you’re shopping, test the basics you’ll touch every day. Specs matter, but comfort is what you live with.',6,1,0,0,3,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(229,47,'The study room schedule that finally stopped me from drifting (XSL139)','I’ve tried a bunch of study schedules, but the one that’s working is basically a “no thinking required” routine. I book the same study room slots, bring the same pouch of supplies, and start with a five-minute warm-up task so I don’t stall. I write finished tasks on the last page of my notebook, which weirdly makes the next day feel lighter. Breaking work into small blocks beats a giant checklist that I’ll ignore. I’m keeping it flexible, but the structure is saving me.',2,1,0,5,4,2,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(230,63,'Library window light is basically a free filter (XSL140)','I did a little phone camera practice by the library window and it reminded me that lighting matters more than any edit. The warm, soft afternoon light made even boring objects look cinematic, so I kept the composition simple: clean lines, a few shadows, and one main subject. I only did light edits because I wanted the colors to stay close to what it felt like in the moment. Next time I want to try the same spot on an overcast day and compare the mood.',4,1,0,6,1,2,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(231,51,'Dorm smart device: the three mistakes I almost made (XSL141)','I picked up a small smart device for my dorm because I wanted a less chaotic desk setup, but I almost bought the wrong one. First, I measured nothing. Turns out the outlet placement and my bed frame make certain shapes super annoying. Second, I ignored noise levels until a friend pointed out the constant hum some models have at night. Third, I forgot about setup friction—if it takes five apps and a reset button, I will stop using it. Now it actually fits my daily routine.',6,1,0,8,3,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:02',0),(232,46,'The only study-room schedule I’ve stuck with all semester (XSL142)','I finally stopped making “perfect” schedules that collapse by Wednesday. What worked: I book shorter blocks (45–60 minutes) and give each block one clear goal, not five. I also plan the “exit step” before I leave the study room—like writing the first line of the next problem set or listing what to open tomorrow. The biggest change is tracking wins on a separate page so the daily plan stays clean. It sounds small, but it makes showing up feel easier.',2,1,0,1,2,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(233,49,'Freshman packing list that won’t overfill your room (XSL143)','Helping a friend pack reminded me how easy it is to bring way too much. My “comfortable but normal” list is basically: one good laundry bag, a small desk lamp, a power strip with enough spacing, shower shoes, a basic first-aid pouch, and two sets of bedding so you’re not panic-washing at midnight. Skip the giant storage bins until you see your actual closet space. Also: bring one “comfort item” (blanket, mug, photo) because the first week feels weirdly long.',3,1,0,1,3,5,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(234,49,'Programming project lessons I learned the hard way (XSL144)','I’m writing this while my project finally runs without exploding. Biggest mistake: I started coding before I wrote down what “done” means. Second: I didn’t set up a tiny test case first, so debugging felt like staring into fog. Third: I kept adding features to avoid the boring parts (documentation, edge cases, refactor). What helped was making a checklist that’s mostly boring tasks and doing them early: naming, folder structure, basic logging, and a simple demo flow. It’s not glamorous, but it saved my sanity.',6,1,0,4,2,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(235,52,'Rain reflections: my favorite library-window shot so far (XSL145)','It rained right when I was leaving the library, so I waited by the window for a few minutes instead of sprinting out. The reflections on the walkway looked messy at first, but dropping my angle lower made the puddles feel like little mirrors instead of random glare. I kept the edits super light—just a touch of contrast and cooler tones—because the real scene already had that soft gray-blue mood. Also, wiping the phone lens mattered more than any filter. I’m weirdly proud of this one.',4,1,0,5,1,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(236,61,'Post-run recovery that fits between classes (XSL146)','I used to finish a run and immediately rush to class, then wonder why my legs felt like concrete the next day. Now I keep recovery painfully simple: water ready before I leave, a slow five-minute walk at the end, then ten minutes of stretching focusing on calves, hips, and hamstrings. If I’m truly short on time, I do just two stretches and breathe slowly instead of skipping everything. The key is consistency, not being intense. It’s the first routine that doesn’t fight my schedule.',8,1,0,6,2,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(237,68,'Dorm smart device review from someone who hates fiddling (XSL147)','I’m not a specs person; I’m a “will I actually use this on a random Tuesday?” person. For dorm smart devices, the dealbreakers are always the same: setup time, reliability, and whether it creates new chores. I tested mine for a week and the biggest win was reducing tiny annoyances (turning things on/off, checking a status, keeping the desk calmer). The biggest downside was cable clutter until I planned where everything would live. If you’re buying one, budget for the boring accessories too.',6,1,0,3,3,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(238,53,'My no-drama morning run log (and why it finally works) (XSL148)','I’m not trying to become a marathon person; I just want my brain to wake up before my first lecture. My run log is ridiculously simple: time, how it felt, and one note (sleep, weather, shoes, whatever). I keep the pace easy enough that I could talk, and I stop before I start negotiating with myself. Afterward I do a quick cooldown and stretch while my coffee brews. The “log” part is what keeps it going—seeing a chain of days is oddly motivating.',8,1,0,6,0,1,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(239,51,'A low-cost weekend route that didn’t feel rushed (XSL149)','I planned a weekend mini-trip and it ended up cheaper than expected because I stopped trying to do everything. I booked transport early, picked one neighborhood to base in, and walked most places instead of bouncing across town. For food, I skipped “famous” spots with long lines and just ate at small places near parks—still great, way less stress. The best part was leaving empty time: sitting by the water, wandering into a bookstore, taking photos. If you’re traveling as a student, calm is the real luxury.',9,1,0,2,1,3,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:10',0),(240,44,'How I prepped for a campus set without burning out (XSL150)','Our club performance is coming up, and I finally found a practice plan that doesn’t make me dread picking up the guitar. I made three mini-playlists: warm-up songs, “confidence” songs, and the ones that still trip me up. Instead of grinding the hard parts for an hour, I do short loops with breaks so my hands don’t get sloppy. I also practiced transitions more than the songs themselves—starting and ending cleanly is what people actually notice. It’s not perfect yet, but it feels steady.',5,1,1,7,3,2,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(241,47,'Closet-corner fall outfit that looks put-together on a student budget (XSL151)','I tried to document a “no-thinking” fall outfit today in the tiny corner by my closet where the light is actually decent. My goal was clean and comfortable, not trendy: neutral layers, one slightly structured piece, and shoes I can walk across campus in without regretting it. The biggest lesson is that repeating basics is what makes mornings easier. If I could only buy one thing this season, it’d be a simple outer layer that works with everything I already own.',7,1,0,2,1,0,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(242,53,'My low-equipment weekly workout plan for busy class weeks (XSL152)','I wrote out a weekly plan that doesn’t require a gym membership or heroic motivation. It’s basically: two easy runs, one bodyweight day, one mobility day, and the rest is walking to class without taking shortcuts. I keep it student-proof by setting everything up first (water, towel, a timer) and leaving ten minutes for cooling down so I don’t feel wrecked before homework. The key is consistency, not intensity. If you’re starting from zero, cut everything in half and just show up.',8,1,0,1,0,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(243,48,'Sticking to one track workout made me feel stronger in class days (XSL153)','I’ve been repeating the same simple track session instead of bouncing between random workouts, and it’s actually doing something. It fits between lectures without turning the whole day into “recovery mode.” I show up with water and a towel, warm up properly, then keep the main set short and honest. The best part is the cooldown: ten minutes of easy walking and stretching so my legs don’t feel like concrete during labs. It’s not flashy, but it’s the first routine I’ve kept for more than two weeks.',4,1,0,8,3,4,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(244,63,'My morning run log: the tiny habit that fixed my sleep schedule (XSL154)','I started keeping a super basic morning run log and it’s weirdly motivating. Nothing fancy: date, distance-ish, how I felt, and one line about what helped (music, breakfast timing, stretching). Because classes get chaotic, I keep the runs short and predictable so I don’t talk myself out of them. I set out water and a towel the night before, then I always leave ten minutes to cool down. The biggest change is my sleep—once I run in the morning, I’m actually tired at night.',8,1,0,5,4,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(245,56,'Monday class outfit: comfy layers that still look intentional (XSL155)','Monday mornings are not when I want to make decisions, so I took a quick outfit photo by the dorm mirror to remember what worked. My rule is: everything has to mix with older pieces, and nothing can be “one-time only.” I went for soft layers, a simple color palette, and shoes that can handle stairs and sudden rain. If I had to pick one thing to invest in, it’d be a basic top layer that instantly makes any outfit look finished. Comfort first, always.',7,1,0,7,1,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(246,45,'What my programming project setup looks like between lectures (XSL156)','I’m deep in a programming class project and finally found a setup that doesn’t feel like a mess. I work in the teaching building study area with a small kit: notebook for quick sketches, a few jumper wires, and the tiny parts that always disappear at the worst time. I’m not chasing specs—I just want something stable that survives being shoved into my bag. The biggest improvement was organizing the workflow: write the plan first, test one change at a time, and log what broke. It saves so much time later.',6,1,0,5,4,1,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(247,49,'Ginkgo walkway after rain: the exact mood I’ve been chasing (XSL157)','I finally got the ginkgo walkway shot I’ve had in my head for weeks. The trick was timing: right after a light rain when the ground reflects, but before the puddles turn into footprints. I kept the edits minimal because the real colors were already perfect—soft yellow leaves, gray sky, and that calm, quiet campus feeling. I also tried a library window frame for a warmer contrast, and it surprised me how cinematic it looked. Next time I want to bring a small cloth to wipe the lens.',4,1,0,3,3,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(248,59,'Lake-bench ginkgo photos: one angle made the whole scene click (XSL158)','I went back to the ginkgo walkway near the lake bench and tried to be more intentional instead of taking twenty random shots. Lowering the viewpoint helped a lot—suddenly the leaves in the foreground, the path, and the trees all had layers. I kept edits light because I’m trying to get better at “seeing” the photo before touching sliders. The sunset glow was tempting, but I liked the softer, warmer window-light look too. Writing these notes makes it easier to repeat the results next time.',4,1,0,8,1,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(249,58,'South gate spicy hotpot bowl: best post-class comfort food for the price (XSL159)','Tried the spicy hotpot bowl near the south gate after class and I get why people line up. It’s best with two or three friends so you can compare add-ins and not over-order. The broth is the kind of spicy that warms you up instead of just burning, and the portion feels fair for a student budget. Biggest tip: avoid the exact class-change rush or you’ll spend half your lunch break waiting. I started noting flavor, price, and wait time so I can actually pick favorites instead of guessing.',1,1,0,7,0,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(250,41,'The vocabulary routine that finally stopped me from cramming (XSL160)','I’ve tried every “study hack” and still ended up cramming, so I built a vocabulary routine that’s boring on purpose. I do short blocks in the department study room: 10 minutes review, 10 minutes new words, 5 minutes quick recall, then a break. The win is reducing friction—when I finish, I write the completed items on the last page so tomorrow starts with a clear entry point. I’m also tracking which words I miss repeatedly and focusing on those instead of re-reading everything. It feels sustainable for once.',2,1,0,1,2,6,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(251,47,'My no-skip quiet study playlist for late nights (XSL161)','I rebuilt my “quiet time” playlist at my dorm desk because my brain has been bouncing all week. The rule is simple: nothing with sudden drums, nothing with lyrics that I’ll start mouthing during readings. I grouped tracks into three phases—settle in, deep focus, and a soft landing for when I’m done. Twenty minutes a day still counts, so I’m trying to make starting feel effortless. Also: headphones off for the last song so I actually notice I’m tired.',5,1,0,0,0,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(252,67,'My student center loop for resetting between classes (XSL162)','I started doing a short “student center loop” when I’m overstimulated or stuck on an assignment. It’s basically a predictable route: one lap outside for air, cut through the lobby to grab water, then back out past the trees. I’m not trying to hit steps goals—just giving my brain a clean break without scrolling. The tiny details help: comfortable shoes, phone on silent, and a hard stop at 12 minutes so it doesn’t become procrastination. It’s weirdly effective.',3,1,0,3,0,3,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(253,61,'Lake bench photo practice: low angles work better (XSL163)','Took my phone to the lake bench after class and treated it like a mini practice session instead of “just taking pics.” The biggest difference was timing—ten minutes earlier than I usually go and the light got softer and less harsh on the water. I also tried dropping the camera lower, almost at bench height, and suddenly the scene had more layers (foreground leaves, water texture, then the buildings). I’m keeping edits super light because I want to learn composition first, not filters.',4,1,0,7,3,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(254,50,'Main road sunset shots that finally look like real life (XSL164)','I went back to the main campus road around sunset and tried to shoot what it actually felt like walking there, not the over-saturated version my phone wants to make. Softer light made everything calmer—less glare on the pavement, more gentle color in the trees. I kept edits minimal: tiny exposure tweak, slight warmth, and that’s it. The best frames came from waiting for the moment when the traffic thinned and the background simplified. Patience is apparently a camera setting.',4,1,0,7,4,2,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(255,44,'A vocabulary routine I can actually repeat in the library (XSL165)','I tested a new vocabulary routine on the third floor of the library and it finally felt… doable. Instead of grinding for an hour, I did three short blocks with a timer and a tiny reward in between (walk to refill water, stretch, back to the desk). The key was reducing decisions: same seat area, same materials, same order—review, quiz myself, then write two example sentences. It’s not glamorous, but it’s repeatable on busy days, which is basically the whole point.',2,1,0,8,0,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:11',0),(256,45,'Milk tea by the east gate: good, fast, not too sweet (XSL166)','Tried the new milk tea spot tucked near the east gate alley because everyone in my class kept mentioning it. The line looked scary but moved quickly, and the staff were efficient without rushing. I ordered a classic milk tea with less sugar and it was balanced—tea flavor first, sweetness second, not that syrupy aftertaste. Price felt fair for a student budget, especially if you’re splitting snacks with friends. I wrote down the wait time and what I ordered so I don’t forget next time.',1,1,0,1,2,2,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(257,60,'Ginkgo walkway shots: rain reflections made it cinematic (XSL167)','Walked past the ginkgo trees by the track bleachers and the whole path felt unusually quiet, especially after the rain. I took a bunch of quick phone photos and the reflections did half the work—puddles basically turned into free mirrors. I kept the color close to what I saw: muted yellow leaves, gray sky, and that warm hint of sunset sneaking through. Next time I want to try the same spot earlier and see how it looks with brighter leaves and fewer shadows.',4,1,0,1,0,3,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(258,66,'A weekly exercise plan that doesn’t collapse by Thursday (XSL168)','I’ve been trying to keep a simple weekly exercise plan and it’s actually sticking because it’s boring in the best way. Two easy runs on the campus path, one strength day with bodyweight stuff, and one long walk when I’m tired. No fancy gear, no “new me” energy—just consistent. I pack water and a small towel before I leave so I don’t talk myself out of going. Also, cooling down for ten minutes helps me not feel wrecked during lectures afterward. Small habits, big difference.',8,1,0,5,0,3,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(259,60,'Dorm stretching that makes my back stop complaining (XSL169)','I started a short stretching routine in my dorm because my shoulders were basically living up by my ears after labs. It’s low intensity and takes about 12–15 minutes, which means I’ll actually do it even on packed days. I usually do it after dinner or right before showering: neck and chest openers, hip stretches, then a slow hamstring stretch. No equipment besides a mat (sometimes just a towel). The best part is it doesn’t steal energy—I feel calmer and sleep faster afterward.',8,1,0,3,0,4,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(260,52,'East gate late-night snack: perfect after study group (XSL170)','After a long study group, we ended up grabbing a late-night snack near the east gate alley and it hit exactly the right spot. The portions were bigger than I expected for the price, and the wait was totally manageable as long as you avoid the peak break between evening classes. It’s definitely better with two or three friends so you can share and try more than one thing without feeling like you over-ordered. I’m adding it to my “tired but hungry” list for the rest of the semester.',1,1,0,7,3,0,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(261,63,'Dorm-Entrance Hotpot Bowl: Worth the Queue? (XSL171)','I finally tried the spicy hotpot bowl right by the dorm entrance and took notes like a total nerd. The portion is bigger than it looks in the display, and it’s one of the few places that doesn’t make me feel robbed on a student budget. Spice level is legit (I needed extra water), but the broth is more savory than oily. Wait time was about 8–12 minutes during dinner rush, faster if you go a little earlier. If you’re sensitive to numbing pepper, ask for less.',1,1,0,8,3,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(262,44,'Laptop Lessons: What I’d Do Differently Next Time (XSL172)','I’ve been using my current laptop setup for a few weeks and I’m relieved I didn’t buy purely off spec sheets. Battery life and fan noise ended up mattering way more than I expected during long lab sessions, and a stable Wi‑Fi card has saved me from so many awkward “my code won’t push” moments. I also underestimated how much I’d appreciate a comfortable keyboard for note-taking. My biggest advice: prioritize the stuff you touch every day (screen, keyboard, ports), then worry about the flashy numbers.',6,1,0,4,4,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(263,44,'My No-Drama Vocab Routine for Busy Weeks (XSL173)','I think I finally found a vocabulary routine that doesn’t collapse the second my schedule gets messy. I sit in the same window seat at the cafe, set a 20-minute timer, and only do one tiny set: review yesterday, add a few new words, stop. The trick that helped most is keeping a “done list” on the last page so I don’t waste energy figuring out where I left off. It’s boring in a good way—less motivation, more autopilot. I’ll update after midterms.',2,1,0,0,0,2,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(264,65,'Quiet Guitar Practice That Actually Adds Up (XSL174)','I started keeping a tiny guitar practice log because I kept “practicing” without remembering what I did. Tonight I focused on rhythm and clean transitions instead of chasing fancy techniques. Twenty minutes felt short, but it was enough to spot the same two spots where my timing falls apart. Writing it down made me way less frustrated because it turned into a plan: tomorrow I’ll slow it down and loop just those measures. Also, practicing quietly is a weird skill on its own when you live with roommates.',5,1,0,8,3,6,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(265,44,'Dorm Smart Device: What’s Useful vs. Just Hype (XSL175)','I added a small smart device to my dorm setup and I’m glad I didn’t overbuy. With a tight budget, I focused on the boring essentials first: reliability, simple controls, and something that won’t randomly disconnect at 2 a.m. The “extra features” are fun, but the daily win is consistency—especially when I’m running between labs and forgetful on no-sleep days. If you’re considering something similar, start with one device that solves one problem (lights, timer, airflow) and live with it for a week before adding more.',6,1,0,0,3,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(266,53,'Morning Run Log: Low Effort, High Payoff (XSL176)','I’m trying to be the kind of person who runs in the morning, so here’s today’s tiny win. I didn’t go hard—just an easy pace that I could keep while half-awake. The best part is it doesn’t wreck the rest of my day: I’m not sore in lecture, and my brain feels less foggy during the first class. I laid out socks and a towel last night and that removed the biggest excuse. If you’re starting, don’t chase distance—just make it repeatable.',8,1,0,3,2,0,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(267,61,'Performance Prep: Small Improvements This Week (XSL177)','This week’s performance prep felt less chaotic than usual, so I’m writing it down before I forget what worked. I kept practice short but consistent—about 20 minutes—and focused on rhythm stability instead of trying to “fix everything.” It’s not glamorous, but my transitions are cleaner and I’m missing fewer beats when I get nervous. I also practiced starting from random spots in the song, which exposed the parts I only knew when I had a running start. Next week: record one run-through and be brave about listening back.',5,1,0,3,4,3,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(268,42,'The White Shirt Outfit I’ll Actually Rewear (XSL178)','I used to think a plain white shirt was boring, but I tried styling it in a way that feels super wearable for campus. The goal was simple: comfortable, clean, and easy to walk in between buildings without thinking about it. I paired it with relaxed pants and shoes I can stand in during long lab days, plus a light layer for classrooms that are always freezing. The best part is everything mixes with stuff I already own, so it doesn’t become a “one outfit” situation. Saving this for busy mornings.',7,1,0,7,2,1,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(269,40,'Affordable Fall Outfit That Survives Long Walks (XSL179)','I took a quick outfit photo today because I’m trying to stop buying “cute but impractical” pieces. This fall look is basically my campus uniform: layers that work from chilly mornings to warm afternoons, and nothing that needs constant adjusting while I’m speed-walking to class. Everything is budget-friendly and easy to rewear—neutral top, comfy outer layer, and pants that don’t wrinkle the second I sit down in the library. If you’re building a closet on a student budget, pick items that can repeat without looking repetitive.',7,1,0,2,0,6,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:12',0),(270,51,'A Weekly Exercise Plan I Can Stick To (XSL180)','I wrote out a weekly exercise plan that’s realistic for class-heavy weeks, not a fantasy schedule. The intensity is moderate and mostly equipment-free: two easy runs, one short strength session, one mobility day, and at least one full rest day. The tiny habit that helps most is prepping water and a towel before I start, then leaving ten minutes to cool down so I don’t feel wrecked afterward. I’m aiming for consistency over “max effort.” If it still feels good after two weeks, I’ll add a little more.',8,1,0,1,3,0,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(271,57,'One-day budget loop from the old street corner (XSL181)','I tried doing a full day out starting from the old street corner without blowing my weekly budget. The biggest win was planning the timing: I took the earliest transit so I wasn’t paying “last-minute” prices, and I kept everything walkable once I arrived. For food, I skipped the touristy spots and just picked two small local places with short lines. I wrote down my route, costs, and the “what I’d do differently” bits so future-me can copy/paste it.',9,1,0,7,2,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(272,51,'Station-start student budget day plan that actually works (XSL182)','If you’re starting at the train station and only have one free day, this is the most “student-proof” plan I’ve found. I mapped a simple loop so there’s no backtracking, and I set a hard cap for snacks so I didn’t accidentally spend more on drinks than on transit. Booking early helped, but honestly the real savings were choosing one paid attraction and making the rest free (parks, small galleries, waterfront). I kept notes on timing, costs, and where I’d take breaks next time.',9,1,0,1,4,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(273,40,'Tried the new milk tea spot by the cafeteria stairs (XSL183)','There’s a new milk tea spot near the cafeteria stairs and I finally tried it between classes. I went with a simple order so I could judge the base flavor, and I timed the line because that’s the real dealbreaker on a packed day. Price is pretty student-friendly, and the cup size felt fair. The sweetness level was more balanced than I expected, and the ice didn’t melt into sad water immediately. I’m keeping this as my “quick treat” option, but I’ll test another flavor next week.',1,1,0,7,2,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(274,43,'My tablet-first study workflow after two weeks of testing (XSL184)','I’ve been experimenting with a tablet-first study setup at my dorm desk, mainly because my backpack is already too heavy. For me, the best workflow is: quick handwritten notes during lecture, then a short “clean-up” session at night where I turn messy pages into something searchable. I’m trying to stay realistic about budget: a solid stylus and a decent stand helped more than chasing specs. The biggest surprise is how much friction matters—if it takes longer than 10 seconds to start, I won’t use it.',6,1,0,7,1,4,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(275,39,'White shirt outfit for long library days (no fuss) (XSL185)','I took a quick photo of today’s white shirt outfit near the study room entrance because it’s my current “default uniform.” When I’m busy, I’d rather have one reliable combo than a closet full of ideas I never wear. I went for clean and comfortable: a slightly oversized white shirt, straight-leg bottoms, and shoes I can walk across campus in without thinking. The key for me is repeatability—everything matches everything, and I can throw on a light layer if the library is freezing. I’ll try a warmer version when it rains again.',7,1,0,5,2,2,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(276,54,'Guitar practice notes that stopped me from plateauing (XSL186)','I started keeping a guitar practice log after rehearsal because I kept repeating the same mistakes without noticing. Today’s focus was boring-but-effective: rhythm, clean chord changes, and staying relaxed instead of speeding up when I get nervous. I also made two tiny playlists by mood—one for studying (soft, steady tempo) and one for breaks (more upbeat) so I don’t end up practicing the same vibe all week. Writing it down makes practice feel less random, and it’s satisfying to see small improvements stack up.',5,1,0,1,1,0,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(277,48,'This week’s rehearsal finally felt less chaotic (XSL187)','Our campus performance prep was a mess last week, so I forced myself to do the unglamorous thing: 20 minutes a day, same time, no excuses. It’s not dramatic, but it’s the first time I’ve felt the progress in my hands—cleaner transitions, fewer random pauses, and I’m not fighting the tempo as much. I also separated songs by energy level so I’m not going from a slow ballad straight into something fast and panicking. The process is still awkward, but it’s way more controlled than before.',5,1,0,0,3,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(278,57,'A weekly exercise plan I can keep on exam weeks (XSL188)','I’ve been trying to stick to a weekly exercise plan that doesn’t collapse the moment assignments pile up. The goal isn’t intensity; it’s consistency. I do short sessions in my dorm: a basic warm-up, a few bodyweight moves, and a quick stretch so I’m not stiff at my desk all day. On days I have more time, I add an easy run, but I’m not forcing it. The biggest change is mental—moving a little makes me less anxious, and I sleep faster. Writing the plan down makes it feel non-negotiable.',8,1,0,7,1,1,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:20',0),(279,63,'10-minute dorm stretching that saved my back this week (XSL189)','My back was wrecked from sitting in labs, so I did a simple dorm stretching routine at the yoga mat corner and I’m weirdly proud of it. I set out water and a towel first because if I have to “go find things,” I’ll quit. I keep it short: hips, hamstrings, shoulders, then a slow cool-down so I don’t jump straight back into scrolling. It’s not a full workout, but it makes studying feel less painful. If you’re tight from carrying a backpack all day, try it for a week and see.',8,1,0,4,0,3,1,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(280,45,'Club rehearsal notes from a quiet study-room corner (XSL190)','We couldn’t get the main practice room today, so we did a low-volume rehearsal in a quiet study-room corner and honestly it helped. Without blasting through songs, we had to listen to timing and dynamics, which is usually what falls apart on stage. I organized the set list by tempo so we warm up gradually instead of starting with the hardest thing and spiraling. I’m also trying to stop chasing flashy technique and just lock in the groove. It’s not glamorous, but it’s the first rehearsal in a while that felt focused.',5,1,0,0,0,5,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(281,54,'Saturday laps + people-watching at the track (XSL191)','I ended up at the track field again this weekend and it felt worth logging, mostly so I can repeat it without overthinking. I did a simple loop: warm-up walk, light jog, then a few strides, and I timed it with my phone so I don’t “accidentally” turn it into a two-hour detour. The best part was the in-between moments—friends cheering each other on, someone practicing hurdles, and the sunset hitting the bleachers. Next time I’m bringing water earlier and leaving my backpack in the shade.',3,1,0,3,4,1,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(282,59,'Chasing soft window light in the library (XSL192)','I took a mini photo set in the library today because the light was doing that calm, golden thing through the tall windows. I tried a few angles and the biggest difference was lowering my viewpoint so the tables and shelves stacked into layers instead of looking flat. Also: waiting five minutes matters more than any filter. When the sun tucked behind a cloud, the highlights stopped blowing out and everything felt softer. I’m writing this down because I always forget the exact time it looks best. Tomorrow I’ll try the same spot closer to closing time.',4,1,0,6,1,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(283,65,'One white shirt, three low-effort campus outfits (XSL193)','I’m trying to be smarter about clothes this semester, so here’s my student-budget white shirt rotation. The goal: clean, comfortable, and repeatable without looking like I’m wearing the same thing every day. Outfit 1: white shirt + straight jeans + sneakers for class. Outfit 2: shirt half-tucked with a knit vest when it’s chilly in lecture halls. Outfit 3: open shirt over a plain tee for a casual “I tried” vibe. The trick is keeping everything neutral so it all mixes. Next purchase is probably a better belt, not another top.',7,1,0,7,2,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(284,60,'Dorm-side noodle counter: honest review (XSL194)','Tried the noodle counter near the dorm entrance again and I think it’s officially my “busy week” safety meal. If you go right after a class break, the line looks scary, but it moves faster than you’d think. I ordered a basic bowl with extra greens and kept it simple—broth was surprisingly clean, noodles had a good bite, and the portion actually filled me up. Best strategy is going with 2–3 friends so you can grab a table while someone orders. Not gourmet, but it’s warm, quick, and student-wallet friendly.',1,1,0,5,4,3,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(285,67,'Quiet library window light at sunset (XSL195)','I went back to the library window spot and it felt even quieter in person than in photos. I kept edits minimal because I wanted the colors to stay close to what I saw: warm highlights, cooler shadows, and that soft gradient right before the sun drops. The main thing I’m learning is timing—ten minutes too early and it’s harsh, ten minutes too late and it’s gone. I also tried to keep the frame simple: one corner of a table, a bit of floor reflection, and the glow. Next time I’ll bring a small notebook to steady my hands.',4,1,0,2,3,1,3,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(286,63,'My low-friction finals review setup at the dorm desk (XSL196)','I’m testing a finals review plan that’s basically designed for my lazy brain. I set everything up the night before: one notebook, one pen, and the exact chapter list on a sticky note (but I put it inside the notebook so it doesn’t become desk clutter). I also write “done” items on the last page so the next day starts with a tiny win instead of decision fatigue. Same time, same chair, same lamp. It’s not glamorous, but it’s been easier to start. If it still works next week, I’ll add a short spaced-repetition block.',2,1,0,8,0,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(287,40,'Post-workout recovery that actually fits dorm life (XSL197)','After a short run I finally did a recovery routine that doesn’t require a gym or a ton of motivation. I cleared a small patch of dorm floor, rolled out a mat, and did a simple flow: calves, hamstrings, hips, then a slow back stretch. Nothing intense—just enough to stop my legs from feeling like bricks the next day. The key for me is keeping it under 15 minutes so I don’t talk myself out of it. I also drink water before I sit down, otherwise I “forget” and scroll for an hour. If you’re sore from campus walking, try the calf stretch first.',8,1,0,7,4,3,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(288,64,'Same library window, different mood (XSL198)','I shot the library window light again, but this time I focused on perspective instead of color. Dropping the camera lower made the scene feel deeper—chairs and table edges turned into leading lines instead of random shapes. I kept the edits light (mostly exposure and a tiny bit of contrast) because the quiet vibe was the whole point. It’s funny how the same spot can look totally different depending on where you stand and how patient you are. I’m saving this as a reference for future shoots when I feel stuck. Next experiment: include a foreground object like a backpack for scale without showing anyone.',4,1,0,1,1,1,0,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(289,41,'Prepping for a small campus set from the bleachers (XSL199)','I did performance prep at the track bleachers today because it’s weirdly good for staying focused. I’m not chasing fancy technique right now—just rhythm, clean transitions, and not tensing up when I mess up. I made a tiny set list and grouped songs by mood so I can switch between “study background” and “actual performance energy.” Also realized I practice better when I stop restarting every time I hit a wrong chord. Play through, mark the problem, fix it after. If anyone has tips for keeping hands warm outside, please share. My fingers were not cooperating.',5,1,0,8,0,5,4,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0),(290,40,'Weekend hostel stay: what I’d do again (XSL200)','Quick notes from my student-budget hostel weekend: booking early made the biggest difference, especially for transport. I picked a place that was slightly outside the busiest area and it saved money without feeling sketchy. The room was basic (bring earplugs), but clean enough, and the common area was great for planning routes. For meals, I didn’t overthink it—small local spots and grocery snacks were totally fine. I wrote down costs and the walk times between spots so I can reuse the plan when I need a reset from campus. Next time I’ll pack a small towel and a lock instead of borrowing one.',9,1,0,1,0,0,2,'1976-06-03 00:34:21',0);
